<h2>Colour Accessibility</h2>
<p>The first one I grabbed straight away from this collection was <strong><a href="http://www.fivesimplesteps.com/products/colour-accessibility" target="_blank">Colour Accessibility</a></strong> by Geri Coady.</p>
<p>This interested me a lot as I have a couple of slightly colour blind colleagues and I always wonder how it is for them to work in design with different levels of colour blindness and I've also wanted to know what I can do when designing to potentially help colour blind users of the web.</p>
<p>First off it was good to learn about the different kinds of colour blindness - something I've only very briefly looked into and also learn how common it is in the general public.</p>
<p>After teaching about this the book then goes on to show simple ways we as web designers can make people with colour defective vision's lives a little easier and after reading it I see no reason not to! In future projects I'll be keeping these techniques in mind as they show ways to tweak your work without sacrificing the aesthetics of a lovely design.</p>
<p>I especially enjoyed the part of the book that uses the London Underground map as an example because I think it's a key example of how an iconic product used by millions of people every year can be tweaked just slightly to make it easier for quite a high percentage of those people who may have a form of colour blindness.</p>
<p>The author then goes on to give some very useful resources for testing your site - viewing through emulators of the different kinds of colour blindness - which I did to some of my sites straight away.</p>
<p>A final piece of advice from Geri is to provide alternative views to your sites such as interchangeable colour schemes and contrasting stylesheets, which I may have a go at implementing on a site in the near future!</p>

