<h2>The Craft of Words - Microcopy</h2>
<p><strong><a href="http://www.fivesimplesteps.com/products/the-craft-of-words-microcopy" target="_blank">The Craft of Words, Part 2 - Microcopy</a></strong> by The Standardistas.</p>
<p>I'd been looking forward to this book since finishing the first part of The Craft of Words <a href="http://daniel.furzeface.com/blog/five-simple-steps-review-collection-two">(see my post on that book)</a>, and I was curious to see how this part would add to and complement what I'd learned from the first.</p>
<p>It didn't disappoint! The authors tell how using the right wording in the smallest places can help enhance a journey and reassure users of the ease of use of your product by showing that you care in every little aspect of your website copy.</p>
<p>It makes sense to me to use this in practise as tying together all parts of the user experience makes for a happy user, obviously! Which in turn will lead to satisfied customers and ultimately more sales of your product.</p>
<p>Throughout the book examples are given of good and bad usability experiences and how they are or could be enhanced using the techniques outlined by the Standardistas and each one leaves you with an "Ahh yes..." moment - wondering why everyone doesn't do this and why you don't do this and when you can next possibly get to a computer to start doing this!</p>
<p>The attention to detail in the case studies shown is astounding and you know that these guys really know their stuff.</p>
<p>I really liked the example of <a href="https://chocolatapp.com/" target="_blank">Chocolat</a> - a text editor that provides a free trial that upon expiration still allows you to use it's full features but every font within the app changes to Comic Sans! Something that every self-respecting designer will cringe at.</p>

