<h2>CSS Animations</h2>
<p><strong><a href="http://www.fivesimplesteps.com/products/css-animations" target="_blank">CSS Animations</a></strong> by Val Head is another one of the Five Simple Steps books aimed at what's possible with the progressive techniques now becoming standards in web development.</p>
<p>It starts from the ground up showing the basic syntax for writing CSS animations such as naming, keyframes, durations and the transforms and transitions possible, and then goes on to give examples on Codepen so you can see along with the code in the book what the animations look like - as well as editing them to create your own.</p>
<p>Easing has often gone over my head when using animations with jQuery before but the chapter in this book on the subject starts to explain the equations behind them a bit more and the graphical representations help clear up what's actually happening when you implement easing into your CSS animations.</p>
<p>I can't think of any practical uses in my own day to day development for some of these animation techniques but the fourth chapter gives some really nice examples of them in everyday use for enhancement of user interfaces on websites and also a pretty good example of using an <a href="http://5ss.co/CSS-animations/CH04/02_Sprite_Animation_With_Steps/" target="_blank">image sprite to create an animation</a> in CSS!</p>
<p>As expected with the books on enhancement techniques the author's final words are on browser support - pointing to one of my most used resources <a href="http://CanIUse.com" target="_blank">CanIUse.com</a>.</p>
<p>A nice feature of the book is the part in the final chapter regarding performance, showing test cases and proving that CSS animation could render faster and use less memory than a JavaScript substitute. I especially find this interesting as any CSS animations I'd probably use would be for mobile enhancements - the fact that they'll probably be supported on modern mobile browsers and also that it'll use less JavaScript is a no-brainer really!</p>
<p>All of this, used with a few examples I've seen on <a href="http://tympanus.net/codrops/" target="_blank">Tympanus</a>, I'll be keeping in mind when I work on a project I currently have where I'm getting to use a lot of modern progressive enhancement techniques.</p>


