<h2>Design Evolution</h2>
<p><strong><a href="http://www.fivesimplesteps.com/products/design-evolution" target="_blank">Design Evolution</a></strong> by Josh Long. I <em>may</em> be in the process of designing a personal project that this next book applies to (hush hush...!) so when I opened it up I was keen to see what advice it could give me on the overall design evolution of a product.</p>
<p>The first chapters delves into breaking down a business and idea into small models to define what exactly it is you want to do and create in order to improve it in small steps, thus refining the entire product.</p>
<p>Next there is a quote that I really like from Antoine de Saint-Exupéry: <em><strong>"Perfection is achieved not when there is nothing more to add, but when there is nothing left to take away"</strong></em> - a quote I've heard many times before and rings true to me. The second chapter talks about how to practically do this and really encourages the reader to refine their idea in order to provide their core service or product at the best possible level.</p>
<p>I'm not sure if it's applicable only to me as I'm in this situation developing a product or if these things are applicable to everyone but as I got more and more into the book I found myself taking notes from every page of this great advice for future reference! The author puts the reader at ease by giving examples of his favourite companies putting these ideas into practise.</p>
<p>The fourth simple step in this pocket guide is about marketing and advertising - something I have a somewhat little amount of real world experience in and the chapter is very useful in defining the best ways to get word of a product out into the market.</p>
<p>Finally there is advice on how to grow through your product, constantly improving and enhancing after feedback and it gave me some great ideas. I think in a month or so I'll be revisiting this very useful guide and the examples shown to apply to my own work!</p>
